29 “LAMPS PURCHASED BY EDUCATION SERVICE DISTRICTS
30
31 “SECTION 21. Section 3, chapter 195, Oregon Laws 2025, is amended to read:
32 “Sec. 3. The amendments to ORS 459.488 by section 2 [of this 2025 Act], chapter 195, Oregon
33 Laws 2025, become operative on [January 2, 2030] the effective date of this 2026 Act.
34 “SECTION 22. ORS 459.488, as amended by section 2, chapter 195, Oregon Laws 2025, is
35 amended to read:
36 “459.488. ORS 459.485 does not apply to:
37 “(1) A lamp used for image capture and projection, including photocopying, printing, directly or
38 in preprocessing, lithography, film and video projection and holography.
39 “(2) A lamp that has a high proportion of ultraviolet light emission and is one of the following:
40 “(a) A lamp with high ultraviolet content that has ultraviolet power greater than two milliwatts
41 per kilolumen.
42 “(b) A lamp for germicidal use, such as the destruction of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid), that
43 emits a peak radiation of approximately 253.7 nanometers.
44 “(c) A lamp used for disinfection or fly trapping from which either:
45 “(A) The radiation power emitted between 250 and 315 nanometers represents at least five per-
HA to HB 4066 Page 3

1 cent of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers; or
2 “(B) The radiation power emitted between 315 and 400 nanometers represents at least 20 percent
3 of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers.
4 “(d) A lamp used for the generation of ozone where the primary purpose is to emit radiation at
5 approximately 185.1 nanometers.
6 “(e) A lamp used for coral zooxanthellae symbiosis from which the radiation power emitted be-
7 tween 400 and 480 nanometers represents at least 40 percent of the total radiation power emitted
8 between 250 and 800 nanometers.
9 “(f) Any lamp used in an electronic product designed to incorporate one or more ultraviolet
10 lamps and intended for irradiation of any part of the living human body by ultraviolet radiation,
11 with wavelengths in air between 200 and 400 nanometers, to induce skin tanning.
12 “(3) A lamp used in a medical device or otherwise used for medical or veterinary diagnosis or
13 treatment.
14 “(4) A lamp used in pharmaceutical product manufacturing or quality control.
15 “(5) A lamp used for spectroscopy and photometric applications, including ultraviolet-visible
16 spectroscopy, molecular spectroscopy, atomic absorption spectroscopy, nondispersive infrared
17 (NDIR), Fourier transform infrared (FTIR), medical analysis, ellipsometry, layer thickness measure-
18 ment, process monitoring or environmental monitoring.
19 “(6) A lamp used by academic or research institutions exclusively for conducting research
20 projects or experiments.
21 “(7) A compact fluorescent lamp used to replace a lamp in a motor vehicle manufactured on or
22 before January 1, 2020.
23 “(8) A lamp purchased by a school district, as defined in ORS 332.002, or an education
24 service district, as defined in ORS 334.003, for use in buildings used to provide educational
25 services to students.
26 “SECTION 23. ORS 459.488, as amended by section 2, chapter 195, Oregon Laws 2025, and
27 section 22 of this 2026 Act, is amended to read:
28 “459.488. ORS 459.485 does not apply to:
29 “(1) A lamp used for image capture and projection, including photocopying, printing, directly or
30 in preprocessing, lithography, film and video projection and holography.
31 “(2) A lamp that has a high proportion of ultraviolet light emission and is one of the following:
32 “(a) A lamp with high ultraviolet content that has ultraviolet power greater than two milliwatts
33 per kilolumen.
34 “(b) A lamp for germicidal use, such as the destruction of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid), that
35 emits a peak radiation of approximately 253.7 nanometers.
36 “(c) A lamp used for disinfection or fly trapping from which either:
37 “(A) The radiation power emitted between 250 and 315 nanometers represents at least five per-
38 cent of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers; or
39 “(B) The radiation power emitted between 315 and 400 nanometers represents at least 20 percent
40 of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers.
41 “(d) A lamp used for the generation of ozone where the primary purpose is to emit radiation at
42 approximately 185.1 nanometers.
43 “(e) A lamp used for coral zooxanthellae symbiosis from which the radiation power emitted be-
44 tween 400 and 480 nanometers represents at least 40 percent of the total radiation power emitted
45 between 250 and 800 nanometers.
